                <TextArea accessibleRole="TEXT" layoutX="64.0" layoutY="459.0" prefHeight="206.0" prefWidth="904.0" style="-fx-background-color: transparent; -fx-border-color: transparent;" stylesheets="@system.css" text="TERMS &amp; CONDITION&#10;1. The payment noted in this record is credited to the current balance of the tenant's lease.&#10;2. The rent has to be paid in total on or before the due date. If the payment is late or incomplete, &#10;fees or notices may be issued.&#10;3. Utility charges, repairs, or damages will be posted to the tenant's account and must be paid &#10;along with the regular payments.&#10;4. The security deposit is kept until the tenant moves out and may be reduced for any unpaid &#10;amounts or repairs of the property after the inspection.&#10;5. This transaction does not alter any rules or agreements that have been stipulated in the lease. &#10;All the existing terms remain in force.&#10;6. By making this payment, the tenant confirms that the amount and details recorded are correct.&#10;7. The tenant must strictly adhere to the lease conditions.&#10;&#10;⸻&#10;&#10;A. FINANCIAL TERMS&#10;&#10;I. Rent Payments&#10;Rent must be paid on or before the due date each month. Accepted payment methods may &#10;include cash, bank transfer, or approved e-wallets. The tenant is responsible for ensuring that &#10;payments are complete and on time.&#10;&#10;II. Security Deposit&#10;A refundable security deposit is required before move-in. This deposit is separate from rent. It&#10;may be used to cover unpaid balances or repair costs after inspection at the end of the lease. &#10;Any remaining amount will be returned to the tenant after clearance.&#10;&#10;III. Advance Payment&#10;An advance payment equal to one month of rent is required before move-in. This serves as &#10;prepaid rent and will be applied to the first or last month of stay, depending on the agreement. &#10;It is not refundable once applied.&#10;&#10;IV. Utilities&#10;Tenants are responsible for paying their own utility bills unless stated otherwise. This may&#10;include water, electricity, gas, and internet.&#10;&#10;V. Refunds&#10;Refunds are only given after moving out and once all charges have been settled and inspection &#10;is completed.&#10;&#10;VI. Payment Records&#10;All payments and charges are recorded in the system and may be viewed by the tenant.&#10;&#10;⸻&#10;&#10;B. OCCUPANCY AND USE RULES&#10;&#10;I. Authorized Occupants&#10;Only the persons listed in the lease may live in the property. A maximum of three occupants is&#10;allowed. Any additional occupant requires approval.&#10;&#10;II. Property Care&#10;Tenants must maintain the property in good condition. Damages caused by negligence or&#10;misuse will be charged to the tenant.&#10;&#10;III. Repairs and Maintenance&#10;Major repairs will be handled by the landlord unless the tenant caused the damage. The tenant&#10;should report problems as soon as possible to prevent further issues.&#10;&#10;IV. Alterations&#10;Changes to the property such as painting, drilling, or installing fixtures are not allowed without&#10;approval. Unapproved changes may need to be removed before move-out.&#10;&#10;V. Noise and Conduct&#10;Tenants must avoid loud noise and behavior that disturbs others. Repeated disturbances may &#10;result in warnings or early termination.&#10;&#10;VI. Pets&#10;Pets are not allowed unless permission is granted. Unauthorized pets may result in penalties or&#10;termination.&#10;&#10;VII. Use of Property&#10;The property is for residential use only. It cannot be used for business or illegal activities.&#10;&#10;⸻&#10;&#10;C. VIOLATION &amp; ENFORCEMENT&#10;&#10;I. Non-Payment of Rent&#10;If rent is not paid, the tenant will receive a notice. Continued non-payment may result in&#10;penalties or eviction.&#10;&#10;II. Property Damage&#10;If the tenant damages the property, the repair cost will be charged to the tenant and added to &#10;the next billing.&#10;&#10;III. Illegal Activities&#10;Any illegal activity may result in immediate lease termination and legal action.&#10;&#10;IV. Disturbances&#10;Repeated complaints about noise or inappropriate behavior may result in warnings or &#10;termination.&#10;&#10;V. Breach of Agreement&#10;If any rule in the lease is violated, the tenant will receive a written notice. Failure to correct&#10;the issue may lead to further action.&#10;&#10;VI. Notice of Violation&#10;Written notice will be given before any penalty or action. Ignoring the notice may result in&#10;eviction.&#10;&#10;VII. Eviction&#10;Eviction may occur if rules are repeatedly violated or serious offenses are committed. All eviction&#10;processes will follow legal procedures.&#10;&#10;⸻&#10;&#10;D. TERMS AND RENEWAL CONDITIONS&#10;&#10;I. Lease Duration&#10;The lease has fixed start and end dates. Leaving before the end without notice may affect the&#10;security deposit.&#10;&#10;II. Renewal&#10;If the tenant wishes to continue staying, they must inform the landlord before the lease ends.&#10;Renewal may include updated terms.&#10;&#10;III. Non-Renewal&#10;If the tenant chooses not to renew, they must move out by the end date. Staying longer without&#10;approval may result in extra charges.&#10;&#10;IV. Early Termination&#10;If the tenant ends the lease early, the deposit may be used to cover unpaid rent or charges. &#10;Notice must be given to allow proper turnover.&#10;&#10;&#10;">
